The plants chosen should be healthy, strong-growers, with a profusion of consistent color. Here is a selection of good plant varieties for creating a carpet bedding:

Coleus - in various shades of red, maroon, and scarlet, light and dark yellow, green and white, and other varieties. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/7d\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/7d\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Achyranthes - low-growing plants in mixtures of red, pink, yellow and green. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/07\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/07\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Centaurea gymnocarpa, "Dusty Miller," - with finely-cut foliage of a cool gray. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/3a\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/3a\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Alternatheras -  similar to Achyranthes in habit, but with red as a predominating color. Both are excellent for working out the finer details of a design. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ab\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ab\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Pyrethrum, "Golden Feather" - with feathery foliage of a tawny yellow. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d1\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet5.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d1\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet5.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Geranium Madame Salleroi - with pale green and white foliage. This is an  excellent plant for use in carpet-bedding because of its close, compact habit of growth, and its very symmetrical shape, which is retained throughout the entire season without shearing or pruning. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ad\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet6.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ad\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet6.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

There are many possible designs. This step provides some examples that you might like to follow. Some of them may seem rather complicated, but when you get down to the business of actually laying them out, any possible complications should be minimized. In laying out all but the star-shaped and circular beds, begin with a square as the basis to work from. Decide on the size of bed you propose to have, and then stake out a square as shown by the dotted lines in design No. 1. Work inside this square, filling in the details. If this is done, creating the carpet bedding will be much easier to achieve. In designing your layout, here are some ideas to inspire you:

Layout design 1 - easy to make, with many possible combinations and modifications. It is best to arrange the colors to suit your individual taste. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/97\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/97\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 2 - a division showing different spaces; a plain center with a plain point as shown in (a), shows the bed in its simplest form. In g, c, and d, these points have three different arrangements and the dotted line in the central portion indicates a change that can be made that will add considerably to the effectiveness of the design. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/03\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/03\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 3{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ad\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/ad\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 4{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2a\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2a\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 5{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fd\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet5.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fd\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet5.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 6{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e5\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet6.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e5\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet6.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 7 - the simplest possible form of bed. This is designed for plants to be set in rows. In a bed of this kind, flowering plants can be used more effectively than in any of the others. Pink, white, and pale yellow Phlox would be very pretty in such a combination. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a9\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a9\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 8 - another very simple design. This design would be quite effective if each of the five sections were of a different color of Coleus. Or, the whole star might be of a solid color, with a border of contrasting color. Red Coleus with Madame Salleroi Geranium as a border would look well. So would yellow Coleus edged with Centaurea. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/4f\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/4f\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Start by making a rough diagram of the bed layout and color this to correspond with the material you have to work with. Seeing these colors side by side on paper will give you a better idea of your proposed combinations. This will allow you to test the design and make changes, helping to avoid making some serious mistakes. If you have a computer design program that you can use easily, this may be another helpful alternative. Here are some interesting combinations to consider:
Ageratum, with its delicate lavender-blue flowers, is very attractive in combination with yellow Coleus{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":572.0879120879121,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A pink Geranium surrounded with gray Centaurea makes a harmonious combination{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8c/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8c/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Scarlet Salvia is very effective with yellow Coleus{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d8/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d8/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A Canna of rich, dark green makes a fine center plant for a bed in which red Coleus served as a background. One of the dark copper-colored varieties has a good effect if surrounded with either yellow Pyrethrum or gray Centaurea. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f0/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f0/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":572.0879120879121,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Caring for the carpet bedding is a key element to its success. Tend the bedding weekly - it is recommended to tend the bedding at least weekly to remove any straggling branches and leaves that are impacting the lines and colors of the design. Run your pruning shears along this line and ruthlessly cut away everything that is not where it belongs. If this is not done on a regular basis, your "pattern" will soon become blurred and indistinct. If any intermingling of colors "from across the line" is allowed, all sharpness of outline will be destroyed. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/30\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/30\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Keep plants clipped - clip frequently to keep the plants dwarf and compact. Make it a point to keep larger-growing plants, such as Coleus, Pyrethrum and Centaurea, under six inches in height rather than over it. Alternatheras and Achyranthes will need very little shearing, as to top, because of their habit of low growth. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":571.0439560439561,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Remove dead or dying leaves and branches - pick these up regularly to keep the design in good shape. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/be\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/be\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":344,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":567.9120879120879,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

