Layout design 7 - the simplest possible form of bed. This is designed for plants to be set in rows. In a bed of this kind, flowering plants can be used more effectively than in any of the others. Pink, white, and pale yellow Phlox would be very pretty in such a combination. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a9\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a9\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Layout design 8 - another very simple design. This design would be quite effective if each of the five sections were of a different color of Coleus. Or, the whole star might be of a solid color, with a border of contrasting color. Red Coleus with Madame Salleroi Geranium as a border would look well. So would yellow Coleus edged with Centaurea. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/4f\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/4f\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-3Bullet8.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Choose the color combination. Start by making a rough diagram of the bed layout and color this to correspond with the material you have to work with. Seeing these colors side by side on paper will give you a better idea of your proposed combinations. This will allow you to test the design and make changes, helping to avoid making some serious mistakes. If you have a computer design program that you can use easily, this may be another helpful alternative. Here are some interesting combinations to consider:
Ageratum, with its delicate lavender-blue flowers, is very attractive in combination with yellow Coleus{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e2\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-459px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e2\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":572.0879120879121,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

A pink Geranium surrounded with gray Centaurea makes a harmonious combination{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8c\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8c\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Scarlet Salvia is very effective with yellow Coleus{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d8\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d8\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

A Canna of rich, dark green makes a fine center plant for a bed in which red Coleus served as a background. One of the dark copper-colored varieties has a good effect if surrounded with either yellow Pyrethrum or gray Centaurea. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f0\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg\/v4-459px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f0\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":572.0879120879121,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Plant the plants. In setting these plants in the bed, be governed by the habit of each plant. Achyranthes and Alternanthera, being the smallest, should be put about four inches apart. Give the Coleus about six inches of leeway, also the Centaurea. Allow eight inches for Madame Salleroi Geranium and Pyrethrum. These will soon meet in the row and form a solid line or mass of foliage. Care for the carpet bedding. Caring for the carpet bedding is a key element to its success. Tend the bedding weekly - it is recommended to tend the bedding at least weekly to remove any straggling branches and leaves that are impacting the lines and colors of the design. Run your pruning shears along this line and ruthlessly cut away everything that is not where it belongs. If this is not done on a regular basis, your "pattern" will soon become blurred and indistinct. If any intermingling of colors "from across the line" is allowed, all sharpness of outline will be destroyed. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/30\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/30\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Keep plants clipped - clip frequently to keep the plants dwarf and compact. Make it a point to keep larger-growing plants, such as Coleus, Pyrethrum and Centaurea, under six inches in height rather than over it. Alternatheras and Achyranthes will need very little shearing, as to top, because of their habit of low growth. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":571.0439560439561,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Remove dead or dying leaves and branches - pick these up regularly to keep the design in good shape. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/be\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/be\/Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Create-Carpet-Bedding-for-the-Garden-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":344,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":567.9120879120879,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}
